   Oblvious to the sudden influx of cursing and swearing from the Erudite casters nearby all of whom's spells fizzled mid cast as the unexpected shouting wood elfess shocked them out of their concentration needed for the spells to work properly, Tanare wondered if this new shop would have her size. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=littanydthule>LittanyDThule</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 51<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(11/13/03 12:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1193.topic&index=34>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A Letter to Meledy singy person</span><hr size=1> She was slammed back against the wall with the force of the rangers voice, and inadvertantly almost bit her tongue.<br>
<br>
Wincing a little she straightened, and took one last look at the prisoner before she silently made her way out of the observation room.  If looks could cause pain, the ranger would have writhed in agony.<br>
<br>
&quot;Can anyone really be this....dense?&quot; She wondered.  There was no fear in the child, none.  &quot;Tanare is too stupid to feel fear, I have heard of such, but never experienced it.&quot; She ground her teeth a little looking at the chaos as she swept by the acolytes chambers.  &quot;She is not suitable, not at all&quot;.  Lord Thule demanded fear in his sacrifices. <br>
<br>
Littany thought back a moment to her meeting the previous evening in the neutralic bazaar with the Meledi and Finarfrin, and her chance encounter with the gnome wizard, Zippus.  Meledi had offered much for the return of the ranger, it was almost tempting.  An offer that could not be trusted to the writing, lest it fall in the wrong hands of either dark or light. And Zippus, she smiled, remembering the foul smell from the wound on his hand and how he tried to conceal it. She laughed as she remembered how the druid offered healing. She had asked later of the Shadows, and confirmed her thoughts, the pox inside that wound would only spread if such was attempted. There was much to consider. She was very tempted also by the subtle irony Zippus suggested.<br>
<br>
&quot;Lord Thule&quot; she at last sank to her knees in front of the altar to pray. &quot;Let me know your will in this, show me a sign&quot;<br>
